Sorry for the long delay in getting back to you; my fall teaching schedule left little room for MathJax questions, I'm afraid.

Your image for the "correct" rendering is not what LaTeX actually produces for `‘P’ f"` in math mode, which is 

<img width="162" alt="primes" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/432782/206792131-65c96c4d-ae46-433a-80c3-964081f84573.png">

Note that the `’` is rendered as a prime symbol, not a quotation mark, in particular, and that is also the case for MathJax.

Because quotation marks are not common in mathematical notation, and because a number of text editors convert `'` and `` ` `` into "smart quotes" `‘` and `’` automatically,  MathJax processes these smart quotation marks as primes and back-primes, and the double quotes as double-primes.  This makes more sense for mathematical notation in most cases. 

The back-prime and double-prime characters are meant to be used within superscripts, and so the characters available for them are larger and on the baseline, and when used as a superscript, they are reduced in size and raises, as any superscript is.  In version 3.2.2 and earlier, the fonts do not include smaller and raised versions of these characters that could be used outside of superscripts, as in your expressions.  (One would need to use `^‘P’ f^"` to get the desired superscript effect.)  In version 4.0 (currently in alpha release) the fonts do include the needed characters to handle both the non-script and superscript versions of these characters, so the `^` will not be needed in the future.

Note, however, that the `'` character is treated specially in both LaTeX and MathJax in that it produces a superscript automatically, so there is no need for `^` in that case.

It is possible to disable the automatic conversion of `‘` and `"` if you wish, using the configuration

``` js
MathJax = {
  startup: {
    ready() {
      //
      //  Don't remap some of the prime-like characters
      //
      const {MmlMo} = MathJax._.core.MmlTree.MmlNodes.mo;
      MmlMo.remapPrimes[0x0022] = 0x0022;  // don't remap double quote
      MmlMo.remapPrimes[0x2018] = 0x2018;  // don't remap smart open quote
      //
      // Do the rest of the usual startup
      //
      MathJax.startup.defaultReady();
    }
  }
}
```

It would be possible to disable the processing of `'` as well, but that is harder, since it is a special character in LaTeX.  I don't recommend doing that, as that would make the output not the same as what LaTeX produces.

OK, I'm not opposed to this idea in principle, but there are a couple of issues.  First, we follow the git-flow model, so pull requests need to be made from a branch that originates from the `develop` branch and are targeted to that branch, so you would need to rebase your `expose-stylelist` branch to originating on the `develop` branch.

Second, I would not want to give access to the actual styles object, as that would allow the user to modify the internal styles structure, which is a bad idea, since that structure needs to be maintained properly to be consistent (e.g., when `border` is changed, `border-left`, `border-right`, etc. must be updated).  So I would recommend making a copy of the object, e.g.,

``` js
  public get styleList(): StyleList {
     return {...this.styles};
   }
```

so that the user gets a private copy of the data rather than the live copy.

This is because the default value for the `scriptminsize` attribute in MathML is set at `8px`, but since the font size is 4px, that means the super- and subscripts will end up being twice as big as the standard text.  The MathML specification says it should be `8pt`, but I ended up switching to `8px` somewhere along the line because 8pt was too big: there are 10pt to an em, and so 8pt is too large in most situations, and it seemed better to have the minimum based on screen pixels in order to avoid too small fonts.  But since `px` are no longer actual pixels, but relative to other scaling factors, as in your example, then that no longer does what it should.

So you might want to set the default minimum script size to something smaller.  For example,

``` js
MathJax = {
  startup: {
    ready() {
      MathJax._.core.MmlTree.MmlNodes.math.MmlMath.defaults.scriptminsize = '8pt';
      MathJax.startup.defaultReady();
    }
  }
}
```

sets it back to `8pt`, which works for your example, but may not work for a real page.  You could use `1px` or something like that, if that works better.

Because the `\overset A{\underset B\leftrightharpoons}` is formed by nested `\overset` and `\underset` commands, the natural translation into MathML is as nested `<mover>` and `<munder>` elements, and so that is what MathJax produces.  If you want `<underover>`, you could use `\overunderset` (this is available in MathJax v3, but not version 2).

It would be possible to use a post-filter on the MathML output of the TeX input jax to look for nested `<mover>` and `<munder>` elements and combine them into a single `<munderover>`.   

Here is a configuration that does that:

``` js
MathJax = {
  startup: {
    ready() {
      MathJax.startup.defaultReady();
      MathJax.startup.document.inputJax[0].postFilters.add(({math, document, data}) => {
        for (const node of data.getList('mover')) {
          const base = node.childNodes[0];
          if (!base || !base.isKind('munder')) continue;
          const mml = data.nodeFactory.create('node', 'munderover', [...base.childNodes, node.childNodes[1]]);
          data.addNode('munderover', mml);
          data.removeFromList('mover', [node]);
          data.removeFromList('munder', [base]);
          node.parent.replaceChild(mml, node);
        }
      });
    }
  }
};
```

This only does `<mover>` with a nested `<munder>`, but you could add a second loop to handle `<munder>` with a nested `<mover>'.  Also, this only works if the `<munder>` is the direct child of the `<mover>`, so no intervening `<mrow>` or `<mstyle>` or other nodes.  Handling that would take a more sophisticated approach.  Also, there might be cases where you want to copy attributes from the original `<mover>` or `<munder>`.

