Using `\underset` is the wrong way to do this.  You want to use `\lim\limits_{x\to c}` to force the limits to be below the "lim".  This is not the way in-line limits are typeset in order to preserve the linespacing between lines of a paragraph.  When the limits are placed underneath, that causes a wider line spacing between the lim containing the limit and the one below, which generally looks bad, and should be avoided.

If you really want this to be the default, you could use the following configuration:

``` js
window.MathJax = {
  startup: {
    ready() {
      MathJax.startup.defaultReady();
      MathJax.tex2mml('\\let\\LIM=\\lim \\newcommand{\\lim}{\\LIM\\limits}');
    }
  }
};
```

which will save the original definition of `\lim` as `\LIM` and then redefined `\lim` to be `\LIM\limits`.  I don't recommend doing it, but that would accomplish what you requested.

MathJax's TeX input jax has a list of valid characters/control-sequences that can be used with `\left` and `\right`, and it only includes the standard TeX ones.  If you want to add more delimiters, you can do so using a configuration like

``` javascript
MathJax = {
  startup: {
    ready() {
      const {Configuration} = MathJax._.input.tex.Configuration;
      const ParseMethods = MathJax._.input.tex.ParseMethods.default;
      const {DelimiterMap} = MathJax._.input.tex.SymbolMap;
      //
      // Create a delimimter map for the new delimiter(s)
      //
      new DelimiterMap('my-delimiters', ParseMethods.delimiter, {
        '\u2016': '\u2016'
      });
      //
      // Create a package configuration that handles the new delimiters
      //
      Configuration.create('my-delimiters', {
        handler: {delimiter: ['my-delimiters']}
      });
      //
      // Do the rest of the usual startup
      //
      MathJax.startup.defaultReady();
    }
  },
  tex: {
    packages: {'[+]': ['my-delimiters']}  // tell TeX to use the new package
  }
};
```

You can list as many delimiters are you want in the `DelimiterMap()`, and if the font in use has stretchy versions of the character, they will stretch when used with `\left` and `\right`.

